=== TASK ===
# Settings / Preferences

## Overview
Create a robust Settings / Preferences area for Roam Resort that empowers authenticated users and hosts to manage personal preferences, account settings, privacy controls, and security. Integrate with Privacy & Legal Compliance Tools to support GDPR/CCPA workflows, including data export and account deletion requests. The UI must be premium, editorial, and consistent with Roam Resort’s luxury brand, while ensuring runtime safety: guard against null/undefined values before using array methods, initialize state with proper defaults, and validate API responses.

---

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A centralized Settings / Preferences hub where authenticated Guests, Hosts, and Concierge admins can view and edit their profile, manage notification and privacy preferences, adjust language/timezone, review security settings, and initiate privacy actions (data export, account deletion) in compliance with GDPR/CCPA.

Goals:
- Provide intuitive, secure access to all user-specific settings in one premium interface.
- Enable granular notification controls (email toggles for inquiry updates, marketing opt-in, reminders).
- Allow users to update identity, contact methods, locale, and time zone.
- Provide security features (change password, view active sessions, log out other devices).
- Seamlessly trigger Privacy & Legal Compliance flows: data export, account deletion requests, and related privacy requests with status tracking.
- Ensure accessibility, performance, and consistency with the project’s design system and safety constraints.

Connected features:
- Privacy & Legal Compliance Tools: privacy requests, data export, account deletion, GDPR/CCPA flows, export CSV, status tracking, and audit trails.
- User roles considerations (Guest, Host, Concierge) determine visible sections and available actions.
- No external APIs required for MVP; architecture should be ready to integrate privacy tools via API endpoints and background workflows.

UI guidance:
- Clear sections with descriptive headings, generous spacing, and editorial imagery where appropriate.
- Use top navigation that becomes solid on scroll; mobile responsive with a hamburger menu.
- Cards with images, titles, descriptive text, and action areas for each settings block.
- Consistent visual language: bronze-gold CTAs, warm beige content backgrounds, navy surfaces, and soft typography.

---

## Components to Build
1) SettingsDashboardLayout
- Purpose: Shared chrome for the Settings area including header, breadcrumb, and section container.
- Technical: React component with slot for sections; responsive grid; accessible keyboard navigation.
- Data needs: none; purely presentational.

2) ProfileOverviewCard
- Purpose: Display current user identity, contact info, and quick actions (edit profile, change password).
- Technical: Card with avatar, name, email mask, edit button.
- Data needs: user object from API; ensure robust guards for missing fields.

3) NotificationPreferences
- Purpose: Toggle controls for:
  - Inquiry updates (email)
  - Marketing communications (opt-in)
  - Reminders (email)
- Technical: Toggle switches with onChange handlers; debounce save or bulk save button.
- Data needs: initial states from user.settings.notifications; must handle missing keys.

4) AccountSettings
- Purpose: Personal details and locale preferences:
  - Name
  - Email (view/edit)
  - Language
  - Timezone
- Technical: Form with validation; save button; inline validation feedback.
- Data needs: currentUser profile; fallbacks for missing locale/timezone.

5) SecuritySettings
- Purpose: Security controls:
  - Change password (modal or inline form)
  - View active sessions
  - Logout other devices
- Technical: Password strength validation; session list fetch; action to terminate sessions.
- Data needs: sessions list; careful handling of sensitive data with minimal exposure.

6) PrivacyActionsPanel
- Purpose: Privacy & Legal Compliance Tools access:
  - Request data export
  - Delete account
  - Download personal data (already available for export)
- Technical: Buttons wired to privacyAPI endpoints; status indicators; initiate flows; export/download UX.
- Data needs: user privacyFlow status; export readiness.

7) PrivacyRequestsStatusTray
- Purpose: Show status of ongoing privacy requests (export, deletion, data access).
- Technical: List with status chips; real-time or polling update.
- Data needs: array of privacyRequests; ensure safe access with guards.

8) HelpTooltip / GuidanceInline
- Purpose: Provide contextual guidance on privacy rights and settings.
- Technical: Accessible tooltips; collapsible guidance blocks.

9) ApiBridge
- Purpose: Centralized API interaction with strict null-safety guards.
- Technical: fetch wrappers that apply data ?? [] guards, parseResponse guards, and consistent shape validations.

10) ValidationMessages
- Purpose: Reusable validation UI for forms (name, email, language, timezone, etc.)
- Technical: Standardized error/success messages with ARIA attributes.

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Frameworks: React + TypeScript; (optional) Next.js for pages/routes; ensure client-side routing to /settings.
- State management: useState for local form state; useEffect for initial data fetch; consider useReducer if complexity grows.
- Data handling:
  - Initialize all array-based state with proper defaults: useState<Type[]>([]).
  - Guard API results: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
  - When consuming API results from Supabase or other sources, use data ?? [] patterns: const items = data ?? [].
  - Never call array methods on potentially null/undefined; wrap with (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
- Components:
  - Accessible and responsive UI with keyboard navigation.
  - Consistent design tokens for colors, typography, radii, spacing per style guide.
  - Cards with hover states; subtle elevation.
  - Forms with proper labels, placeholders, and focus rings in accent color.
  - Toggle switches with clear on/off states and accessible labels.
  - Modals for password change and privacy actions with proper aria-modal, focus trap, and ESC handling.
- Data flows:
  - Fetch currentUser and related settings on mount.
  - Provide optimistic UI updates with graceful error handling.
  - Persist changes via PATCH/PUT requests; handle partial saves and show toasts/inline messages.
- Error handling:
  - Graceful UI for failed requests; retry strategies; user-friendly messages.
- Accessibility:
  - Semantic HTML, aria-labels, proper color contrast, keyboard focus indicators.
- Design system integration:
  - Apply typography, color palette, card styling, navigation patterns, and interactive elements per Visual Style section.

### Backend
- API Endpoints (defined, to be implemented or wired):
  - GET /api/users/me/settings
  - PATCH /api/users/me/settings (partial updates for profile, locale, timezone, notification preferences)
  - POST /api/privacy/export (initiate data export; returns exportId and status)
  - GET /api/privacy/export/{exportId} (poll export status or download link)
  - POST /api/privacy/delete (initiate account deletion; requires confirmation)
  - GET /api/privacy/requests (list privacy-related requests for current user)
  - POST /api/auth/change-password (change password)
  - GET /api/sessions (list active sessions)
  - POST /api/sessions/logout-others (invalidate other sessions)
- Data models:
  - UserProfile: id, name, email, language, timezone, avatarUrl, preferences { notifications: { inquiryUpdates, marketing, reminders } }
  - PrivacyRequest: id, type (export, delete, access), status, createdAt, updatedAt
  - Session: id, device, lastActive, ip
  - ExportJob: id, status, downloadUrl, createdAt, completedAt
- Validation:
  - Server-side validation for all updates; ensure null-safe returns.
- Security:
  - Ensure endpoints require authentication; protect sensitive actions with CSRF where applicable; proper authorization for role-based access in multi-user flows.

### Integration
- Data layer:
  - Client fetches from /api/users/me/settings for profile and preferences.
  - Privacy tools flows trigger /api/privacy/export and /api/privacy/delete; status polled via /api/privacy/export/{exportId} and /api/privacy/requests.
- UI flows:
  - Settings sections load in parallel; show skeletons while loading.
  - Changes saved with optimistic update; show success/error toasts.
  - Privacy actions gated by consent and confirmation dialogs; data export and account deletion require explicit confirmation steps.
- Data safety:
  - All array interactions guarded: const items = Array.isArray(data?.items) ? data.items : [].
  - Product-wide use of data ?? [] for Supabase-like results when mapping arrays.

---

## User Experience Flow
1) User navigates to Settings / Preferences from main navigation.
2) Page loads: profile, notification prefs, account info, security settings, and privacy tools sections render with current values.
3) User updates Notification Preferences:
   - Toggles update state; “Save” button appears or changes auto-save; success notification shown.
4) User updates Account Settings:
   - Edits name, email, language, timezone; validation messages shown inline; save updates on submit; success toast.
5) Security:
   - User opens Change Password modal; enters current password, new password, confirmation; validations applied; on success, show confirmation.
   - User views Active Sessions; can terminate other devices; confirm destructive action.
6) Privacy Actions:
   - User clicks “Request data export”; flows to privacy export: asks for confirmation if needed; initiates export; status updates appear in PrivacyRequestsStatusTray.
   - User can initiate “Delete account” with safety confirmations; status tracked; if deletion is processing, disable conflicting actions.
7) Privacy Requests Status:
   - User can monitor all privacy-related requests (export, delete) with statuses (Pending, In Progress, Completed, Failed).
   - If export is ready, a download link is shown.
8) Help/Guidance:
   - Inline tooltips or help panels provide user rights under GDPR/CCPA and privacy tool guidance.

---

## Technical Specifications

Data Models: Schema details
- UserProfile
  - id: string
  - name: string
  - email: string
  - language: string
  - timezone: string
  - avatarUrl?: string
  - preferences?: {
      notifications?: {
        inquiryUpdates?: boolean
        marketing?: boolean
        reminders?: boolean
      }
    }
- PrivacyRequest
  - id: string
  - type: 'export' | 'delete' | 'access'
  - status: 'Pending' | 'InProgress' | 'Completed' | 'Failed'
  - createdAt: string
  - updatedAt: string
- Session
  - id: string
  - device: string
  - lastActive: string
  - ip: string
- ExportJob
  - id: string
  - status: 'Queued' | 'InProgress' | 'Completed' | 'Failed'
  - downloadUrl?: string
  - createdAt: string
  - completedAt?: string

API Endpoints: Routes and methods
- GET /api/users/me/settings
- PATCH /api/users/me/settings
- GET /api/users/me
- POST /api/auth/change-password
- GET /api/sessions
- POST /api/sessions/logout-others
- POST /api/privacy/export
- GET /api/privacy/export/{exportId}
- POST /api/privacy/delete
- GET /api/privacy/requests

Security: Authentication, authorization requirements
- Ensure all endpoints require authenticated user session.
- Role-based visibility: Guests, Hosts, Concierge Admins see appropriate sections; non-admins restricted where necessary.
- Use HTTPS, CSRF protection for state-changing actions, and proper token-based auth for API calls.
- Do not leak sensitive data in responses; mask emails where not strictly necessary.

Validation: Input validation rules
- Name: non-empty, reasonable length (2-100).
- Email: valid email format; allow edits only if user is permitted.
- Language: from supportedLanguages list.
- Timezone: from supportedTimezones list.
- Password: strength requirements (min length, complexity).
- Notification toggles: booleans; default to existing state or false.
- Privacy actions: confirm prompts; prevent duplicate requests.

